lated</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> communities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.35pt; padding-left:8.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Great</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Britain has an extensive </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rail network</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">- </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">2,532 passenger stations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">14,504 route kilome</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tres open for passenger traffic – that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">extends</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">from our largest cities to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">some of the most isolated communities in England, Scotland and Wales.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How do </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Government and local authorities identify demand for passenger transport in isolated communities (including rural and urban areas and island communities)?</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.35pt; padding-left:8.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">UK, Scottish and Welsh government</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> identify demand in isolated communities and determine whether and h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ow this demand should be served by rail</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Government</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> de</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cide</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">routes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">must be served</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, along with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">specifications</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> relating to timetables and stopping patterns</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ompanies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">then </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">bid for the right to operate the franchise to th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> specification</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Financial </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">support is provided within</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> many</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> franchises</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to enable train companies to operate services </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">deemed to be socially necessary that would not otherwise be sustainable on a commercial basis.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.35pt; padding-left:8.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">flexibility and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">success of the franchising model over the last 15 years </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">help</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Government to support </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">these </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">services. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.35pt; padding-left:8.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Splitting</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the network into </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">distinct franchises </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">allow</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the governments to focus</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> clearly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> on the indi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">vidual needs of different areas and ensure thos</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e needs are met within each franchise agreement. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.35pt; padding-left:8.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Opening the network to multiple operators, competing to operate franchises and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">incentivised to attract more passengers, has lead to innovation and improvement</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">assengers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> have responded with their feet.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.35pt; padding-left:8.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There has been an unprecedented 73% increase in the number of passenger journeys over the last 15 years - from 845 million to 1,460 million</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> -</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> generating record levels of revenue.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> £3.2 billion increase in annual passenger revenue</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of which 96% has come</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> from journey </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">growth and just 4% from fare changes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">plus train companies controlling their operating costs means the money generated for Government has increased by £1.3 billion - from £400 million to £1.7 billion</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> – over the last 15 years. This additional </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">money can be used to support non-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">commercial</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> services in addition to being reinvested back into the railway infrastructure.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.35pt; padding-left:8.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In addition, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">open access operators have entered the market to operate services where they spot a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> market</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> opportunity, but they need</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> serve routes with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> sufficient demand </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">generate a commercial return</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in the absence of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">direct </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Government support.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 25.1pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What are the main challenges associated with providing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> and funding</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> better and more consistent bus and rail services to isolated communities? How can these challenges be overcome?</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> How can these services be made more affordable?</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.35pt; padding-left:8.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The main challenge to providing rail services to isolated communities is ensuring that a value </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for money and sustainable service can be run. Often other passengers and taxpayers are ultimately subsidising the service, so it is important that the business case is closely scrutinised. The franchise specification and level of Government support provide</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d to deliver that specification will largely determine the service provided.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36.93pt; padding-left:2.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">One mechanism for sustaining and developing rail access to isolated communities is through the development of Community Rail Partnerships (CRPs). CRPs play an important role in increasing the use of lines that are not commercially viable by providing volun</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">teer support to help improve and run stations, by attracting inward investment to develop stations, by transforming stations into a broader community resource, and by driving up rail usage through promotional events and activities. CRPs bring together a nu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mber of disparate interests who have an interest in the success of their local railway.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There were over 23.5 million journeys on the 34 DfT-designated CRP lines in 2012.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> The number of journeys on these lines has increased by 21.3% since 2009.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36.93pt; padding-left:2.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ATOC and th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e train companies work closely with the Association of Community Rail Partnerships (ACoRP) to support these activities.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> ACoRP represents CRPs and station supp</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ort groups across the country.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It has 39 CRP members covering 73 lines and 122 station support gr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">oups.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It provides training and supports research into the potential and benefits of applying community rail principles, disseminates good practice and manages two grant schemes which provide encouragement and support for community projects that bring be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nef</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">its to the lines concerned.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ith the cooperation of ATOC</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> it</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> also monitors the community rail line passenger numbers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to identify trends and the benefits flowing from initiatives promoted by CRPs.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36.93pt; padding-left:2.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Many local authorities appreciate the value of community rail</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and have supported it where they can, but spending on rail is vulnerable because it is discretionary and not a statutory requirement. Pressure on budgets has caused many local authority partners to reduce their </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">financial support to CRPs, and some to withd</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">raw support altogether.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> This is starting to cause problems for some partnerships. </span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 25.1pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">To what extent are the needs of different groups of passengers (e.g. people with disabilities, older people and younger people) taken into account in determining the provis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ion of public transport to isolated communities?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 17.85pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Multimodal access to stations</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36.93pt; padding-left:2.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ATOC a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nd </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">train operators have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">placed a good deal of focus on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">this important area for passengers, implementing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a number of schemes that increase </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rail access </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to and from</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> other forms of transport</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, making travel by rail as part of a door to door journey easier, cheaper and accessi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ble </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> more members of society</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36.93pt; padding-left:2.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Improving bus access can particularly benefit older people and people with disabilities.  ATOC has worked closely</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> with public transport operators via the Journey Solutions Partnership to provide a rail/bus integrated ticket called PLUSBUS at around 250 locations across the UK. The ticket provides reduced cost onward travel for those purchasing their rail and bus tick</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ets through this offering. This </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">offer is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> very popular with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Rail</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">card users, particularly 16-25 Railcard holders, who receive an additional </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1/3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> discount on top of the existing saving provided by the combined ticket. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Almost one million PLUSBUS tickets are now</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> sold every year.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36.93pt; padding-left:2.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In communities where bus services</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> are limited,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> improving cycle access can particularly help younger and older passengers. Improving </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">cycling facilities at stations extends the practical catchment area of station by up to 5 miles. ATOC and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">its </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">partners in the Cycle Rail Working Group are currently implementing a programme of works which will </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">result in the number of cycle parking spaces at </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">stations nearly triple from 2009 levels to around 70,000 cycle parking spaces and around 1,500 hire cycl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">es by 2015. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Cycle-rail use </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">has grown</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> by around four million </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">annual </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">journeys </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">over </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the last three years.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36.93pt; padding-left:2.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Improved cycle facilities at stations</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">can also help attract</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> commerce </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to isolated communities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">through sustainable tourism. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">For example,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">First TransPennine</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Express ha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> teamed up with the Electric Bicycle Network to encourage people to explore the Lake District with an electric bike and offer 20% off ebike hire when </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> travel to the Lake District by train. Scotrail </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">also</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> offers </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">an innovative discounted</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> bik</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e hire scheme, allowing cyclists to enjoy scenic </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">one-way </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">journeys across the Highlands. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36.93pt; padding-left:2.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Station travel plans (STPs) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">provide a co-ordinated approach to station access </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">by various forms of transport. They also provide a forum for cross-organisational partner</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ship working with other public transport providers, local communities, co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">uncils and other stakeholders, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">which helps train companies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to devise tailored solutions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> at each station location</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There are presently around 100 STPS in existence with more planned. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">New guidance p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ublished</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ATOC and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Rail Safety and Standards Board</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> recommends the implementation of the STP approach at all stations. </span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 17.85pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Making stations and trains more accessible</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline"> in isolated communities</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36.93pt; padding-left:2.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Our </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">work around accessibility addres</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ses the rail </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">network as a whole, but</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> some initiatives have particular benefits for disabled</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and older</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> passengers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> with limited mobility</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> living in isolated communities.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36.93pt; padding-left:2.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Although </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pproximately 60% of rail stations are accessible, many passengers require help when boarding</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> trains. The stepping gap between platform and train creates particular difficulties for wheelchair users and visually impaired passengers. The network-wide Passenger Assist booking system enables passengers to pre-book boarding ramps to overcome this prob</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lem.</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36.93pt; padding-left:2.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">H</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">elp</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> through Passenger Assist</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> is available at every station across the rail network, including </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">unstaffed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">stations in rural and isolated communities. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">At those stations train companies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> roster staff to be available at </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the station, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">use on board staff to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> deliver assistance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> or </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">provide</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> taxis so that passengers can be transported to the nearest station with staff available to help. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36.93pt; padding-left:2.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The latter option is made more difficult by the fact that not all local authorities have licensed accessible taxis. This means</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that considerable additional costs </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">can </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">arise when procuring taxis in some rural </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">areas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, with taxis often needing to be procured from businesses </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">located </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">some distance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> away</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> from the station where they are required. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36.93pt; padding-left:2.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Platform humps offer an alternative </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to boa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rding ramps for boarding trains. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The humps enable part of the platform to be raised to create level access betwe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">en the train and the platform. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Humps still leave a small gap and do not entirely resolve the difficulties for all wheelchair users (some wheelch</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">air users do not have the ability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to negotiate the residual gap), but</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">any passengers with mobility impairments have found that platform humps offer a reasonable alternative to using boarding ramps and remove the need to pre-book assistance for that partic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ular part of the journey.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rain companies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and Network Rail are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> using </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">funding</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> available</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> under the Medium Schemes programme of Railways for All to install humps at 63 stations, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> majority</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in isolated and rural locations. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36.93pt; padding-left:2.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">O</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">lder and disabled passengers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> can also benefit from ATOC’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tations Made Easy (SME) service, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">delivered through the National Rail Enquires website.</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">SME contains access information </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">every station on the network and allows passengers to evaluate whether or not they can use any given </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">station. Passengers can plan a route through stations based upon their own access preferences. They can also see what facilities exist </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> evaluate if they are able to use that particular station. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36.93pt; padding-left:2.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Anecdotal evidence suggests that many passengers have been </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">able to use SME to identify better stations from which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> travel. For example</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> we received feedback from a member of a Government advisory committee that their journey time had been reduced by 40 minutes because, using </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">SME</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, they were able to identify a sta</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tion much closer to their home in rural Scotland rather than travelling to a station further away.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 21.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Targeted r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">ailcards</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36.93pt; padding-left:2.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Younger people, older people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and people with disabilities living in isolated communities can reduce the cost of their train travel by purchasing an appropriate railcard. A 1/3 discount off rail fares is available with a 16-25 Railcard, a Senior Railcard, and a Disabled Persons Railca</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rd.</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18.3pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Using Information technology</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36.93pt; padding-left:2.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The internet and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">smart</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">phone technology is helping to improve information and service provision for people in isolated communities. For example, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the National Rail Enquiries website and its apps for smartphones allow users </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to access real time departure and arrival information for all rail stations. In addition, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">many train companies are rolling out the opportunity to self print tickets or have tickets sent to a mobile phone which reduces dependence on ticket vending machines </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and ticket offices. </span></li></ol></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">ORR Statistics, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic">Infrastructure on Railways</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> table</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">For example, in many isolated communities served by rail, evening and Sunday</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> services are provided as part of the franchise specification. This often compares favourably to bus provision, where many local bus services either don’t operate after 6-7pm or are severely curtailed.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">Richard Brown’s recent review of franchising conclud</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">es</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic">‘since privatisation, Britain’s railways are successfully carrying more passengers, more safely, on many more and newer trains, more of which arrive punctually and with greater levels of passenger satisfaction.’</span><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/49453/cm-8526.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/49453/cm-8526.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">egional journeys</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">have increased by 65% - from 206m journeys t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">o 340m journeys.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> ATOC, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic">Growth and prosperity: how franchising helped tr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic">ansform the railway into</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; font-style:italic"> a British success story</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">, July 2003, p.16</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/community-rail-routes"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/community-rail-routes</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> For more information visit </span><a href="http://www.acorp.uk.com/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.acorp.uk.com/</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn8"></a><a href="#_ftnref8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a href="http://www.rssb.co.uk/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; f